-{"id":"beads_rust-dcph","title":"fsync parent directories after atomic JSONL/config/history renames","description":"Lens: Data integrity

Finding: Several atomic rewrite paths sync the temporary file before `rename`, but do not fsync the parent directory after the rename. That protects against many process-level partial writes, but it leaves weaker durability under power loss or filesystem crash: the new directory entry may not be durable even though docs describe atomic writes as corruption-safe.

Evidence:
- `src/sync/mod.rs::write_jsonl_lines_atomically` calls `sync_all` on the temp file and then `fs::rename`, with no parent directory fsync.
- `src/cli/commands/config.rs::write_config_atomically` has the same temp-file sync then rename pattern.
- History/backup rewrite paths should be reviewed for the same pattern.

Acceptance criteria:
